11 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
12 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law not to be
13 codified in the Oklahoma Statutes reads as follows:
14 A. It is the intent of the Legislature to ensure educational
15 excellence in this state by making informed decisions in support of
16 students in this state, their education, and the future
17 contributions they will make to the workforce.
18 B. The Legislature finds that a responsible government ensures
19 that taxpayer dollars are expended in the manner directed by the
20 Legislature and are providing a return on investment for Oklahoma’s
21 future.
22 C. To protect the hard-earned dollars of taxpayers in this
23 state, the Legislature must be able to comprehensively evaluate
24 student and workforce data to make decisions and reforms where
ENGR. S. B. NO. 224 Page 1

1 nece ssary while safeguarding the confidential information of
2 Oklahomans.
3 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
4 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3-180 of Title 70, unless there
5 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
6 A. There is hereby created the Oklahoma Education and Workforce
7 Efficiency Data System (EDS) as a secure system for the de-
8 identification, exchange, and matching of education and workforce
9 data among approved entities. The purpose of the EDS shall be to
10 provide state agencies, legislators, and other approved users with
11 access to de-identified data on early childhood education,
12 elementary and secondary education, workforce training, and
13 employment outcomes to improve education and workforce outcomes and
14 increase the return on investment for taxpayer funds.
15 B. The EDS shall have the ability to:
16 1. Access, ingest, integrate, and transform a variety of data
17 types to and from the Oklahoma Workforce Commission, the Oklahoma
18 Department of Career and Technology Education, the State Department
19 of Education, the Oklahoma Employment Security Commission (OESC),
20 the Oklahoma State Regents for Higher Education, the Regional
21 University System of Oklahoma (RUSO), the Office of Educational
22 Quality and Accountability (OEQA), and any other agency that
23 collects critical employment or education data;
24
ENGR. S. B. NO. 224 Page 2

1 2. Be designed to allow additional agencies to integrate their
2 data in the future;
3 3. Implement identity management capabilities to create unique
4 identifiers to restrict personally identifiable information while
5 linking early childhood education, elementary and secondary
6 education, postsecondary education, and workforce data;
7 4. Enable data governance, auditing, and tracking of data edits
8 and changes by authorized users;
9 5. Support advanced analytics capabilities including, but not
10 limited to, artificial intelligence, machine learning, forecasting,
11 and data mining, as well as the use of business intelligence tools
12 such as data visualization and dashboards; and
13 6. Ensure compliance with the Family Educational Rights and
14 Privacy Act of 1974 (FERPA), the Student Data Accessibility,
15 Transparency and Accountability Act of 2013, and other applicable
16 privacy laws.
17 C. The EDS shall not:
18 1. Serve the same purpose as the state student identification
19 system required by subsection E of Section 18-200.1 of Title 70 of
20 the Oklahoma Statutes;
21 2. Directly report data to federal agencies; provided, however,
22 state agencies participating in the EDS may use matched data from
23 the EDS to fulfill federally mandated reporting requirements
24 including, but not limited to, compliance with the Workforce
ENGR. S. B. NO. 224 Page 3

1 Inno vation and Opportunity Act, the Carl D. Perkins Career and
2 Technical Education Act of 2006 as reauthorized by the Strengthening
3 Career and Technical Education for the 21st Century Act, the
4 Workforce Data Quality Initiative, and other workforce- and
5 education-related federal grant programs. Any data used for such
6 purposes shall be de-identified or aggregated before submission,
7 unless federal law explicitly requires otherwise; or
8 3. Collect personal data including, but not limited to, the
9 religion of an individual and his or her parent or legal guardian;
10 the political affiliation of an individual and his or her parent or
11 legal guardian; the health insurance status of an individual and his
12 or her parent or legal guardian; and medical information relating to
13 an individual and his or her parent or legal guardian.
14 D. The EDS shall provide controlled access to approved external
15 partners including researchers or vendors, ensuring compliance with
16 privacy protections. Data access shall be granted through a formal
17 data-sharing agreement submitted to the Efficiency Data System
18 Governance Council created pursuant to Section 3 of this act, with
19 guidelines on usage and restrictions to safeguard personally
20 identifiable information.
21 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
22 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 3-181 of Title 70, unless there
23 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
24
ENGR. S. B. NO. 224 Page 4

1 A. There is hereby created the Efficiency Data System
2 Governance Council to oversee the development, implementation, and
3 operation of the Oklahoma Education and Workforce Efficiency Data
4 System (EDS) created pursuant to Section 2 of this act. The Council
5 may create committees, as needed, to delegate and carry out its
6 duties.
7 B. The Council shall be comprised of nine (9) voting members as
8 follows:
9 1. The Executive Director of the Oklahoma Workforce Commission,
10 or his or her designee;
11 2. The Chancellor of Higher Education, or his or her designee;
12 3. The Director of the Oklahoma Department of Career and
13 Technology Education, or his or her designee;
14 4. The Superintendent of Public Instruction, or his or her
15 designee;
16 5. The Executive Director of the Oklahoma Employment Security
17 Commission, or his or her designee;
18 6. The Executive Director of the Office of Educational Quality
19 and Accountability, or his or her designee;
20 7. The Chief Executive Officer of the Regional University
21 System of Oklahoma (RUSO), or his or her designee;
22 8. One data privacy and security expert who is familiar with
23 the Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act of 1974 (FERPA), the
24 Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) of 1996,
ENGR. S. B. NO. 224 Page 5

1 and national privacy standards, appointed by the Commission for
2 Educational Quality and Accountability; and
3 9. One member of the public with expertise in workforce or
4 education policy, data analysis, or government efficiency, appointed
5 by the Governor.
6 C. The Efficiency Data System Governance Council may include
7 non-voting members from additional state agencies, institutions of
8 higher education, or stakeholder groups as needed to provide
9 subject-matter expertise.
10 D. The Efficiency Data System Governance Council shall:
11 1. Oversee all aspects of data governance including approving
12 data access policies, privacy standards, and data-sharing
13 agreements;
14 2. Identify and prioritize critical data elements and datasets
15 for initial integration in the system by June 30, 2026;
16 3. Outline a process to approve and onboard new agencies to the
17 EDS;
18 4. Select a vendor for the development and maintenance of the
19 EDS, ensuring the vendor meets the system requirements and technical
20 specifications approved by the Efficiency Data System Governance
21 Council by June 30, 2026. Funding and procurement responsibilities
22 shall be assigned to the Commission for Educational Quality and
23 Accountability, with the EDS housed within the Office of Educational
24 Quality and Accountability;
ENGR. S. B. NO. 224 Page 6

1 5. Electronically submit an annual progress report to the
2 Governor, the President Pro Tempore of the Senate, and the Speaker
3 of the House of Representatives summarizing the progress of the EDS,
4 completed milestones, next steps, challenges, and recommendations
5 for improvements. The first report shall be submitted by June 30,
6 2026; and
7 6. Ensure the EDS is operational and includes critical datasets
8 no later than June 30, 2027.
9 E. By June 30, 2026, each agency participating in the EDS shall
10 enter into a data-sharing agreement with the Efficiency Data System
11 Governance Council. The agreement shall include:
12 1. Data-sharing protocols;
13 2. Data elements shared;
14 3. Data elements requested;
15 4. Roles and responsibilities for the participating agency and
16 the Council; and
17 5. Privacy and security standards.
18 F. The EDS shall be funded through:
19 1. State appropriations provided to the Office of Educational
20 Quality and Accountability for the specific purpose of procuring and
21 maintaining the EDS;
22 2. Federal grants including, but not limited to, funding
23 opportunities from the Workforce Data Quality Initiative or other
24 federal programs;
ENGR. S. B. NO. 224 Page 7

1 3. Cost-sharing agreements or user fees approved by the
2 Efficiency Data System Governance Council; and
3 4. Public or private sources, provided such funds are
4 consistent with the purpose and goal of the EDS.
5 G. The Commission for Educational Quality and Accountability
6 may promulgate rules to implement the provisions of this act.
7 SECTION 4. This act shall become effective July 1, 2025.
8 SECTION 5. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
9 of the public peace, health, or safety, an emergency is hereby
10 declared to exist, by reason whereof this act shall take effect and
11 be in full force from and after its passage and approval.
